%% Related Work

\subsection{Diffusion Models and Resolution Flexibility}
Recent advances in generative modeling have focused on diffusion-based frameworks where a stochastic diffusion process is reversed to synthesize high-quality images. Early works such as \citet{ADM} and \citet{LDM} laid the foundation for score-based generative models, and subsequent studies integrated transformer architectures into diffusion, as demonstrated by the Diffusion Transformer (DiT) \cite{DiT}. 

A major limitation of many diffusion models is their reliance on a fixed-resolution grid during training. Cropping or resizing operations may introduce biases that hinder a model’s ability to generalize to arbitrary resolutions. In contrast, frameworks such as FiT \cite{FiT} use dynamically sized tokens and advanced positional embedding strategies (e.g., 2D rotary embeddings) to preserve the original aspect ratio, thereby enhancing resolution generalization and mitigating biases caused by fixed-grid processing.

\subsection{Accelerated Sampling and High-Order Numerical Solvers}
A critical bottleneck in diffusion models is the slow convergence of the reverse diffusion process, particularly for high-resolution images. \citet{AcceleratedSampler} propose accelerated sampling techniques that leverage higher-order ordinary differential equation (ODE) solvers. By incorporating adaptive step-size corrections, these methods improve the convergence rate from \(O(1/T)\) to \(O(1/T^2)\), enabling faster image generation while preserving output quality.

\subsection{Flexible Architectures with Dynamic Tokenization}
The transition from fixed-resolution grids to token-based image representations has had a significant impact on diffusion modeling. For example, the FiT framework preserves image aspect ratios and supports both training and inference over a wide range of resolutions without incurring cropping biases. Building on this idea, our work introduces several key innovations:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Dynamic Token Acceleration:} A module that applies a momentum-inspired corrective term to update token representations. A linear transformation of the token features is combined with a scaled contribution from the features of the previous iteration, thereby permitting larger diffusion steps while maintaining image fidelity.
    \item \textbf{Adaptive High-Order ODE Solver:} Instead of relying on traditional first-order integration schemes such as DDIM, our approach employs an adaptive second-order solver that computes token-wise updates with integrated error correction. This significantly reduces the number of diffusion steps required and accelerates convergence.
    \item \textbf{Joint Backbone and Sampler Training:} The model is trained end-to-end by simultaneously optimizing the transformer backbone and the accelerated sampling module. A composite loss function that balances a conventional denoising objective with a secondary term enforcing consistency across diffusion step sizes is used to achieve this integration.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Dynamic Token Acceleration Module: Pseudocode}
The following algorithm summarizes the dynamic token acceleration mechanism and its integration within transformer blocks.

\begin{algorithm}[H]
\caption{Dynamic Token Acceleration Module}
\label{alg:token_acceleration}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
    \State \textbf{Input:} Token features \(T\), previous features \(P\), momentum factor \(\mu\) (default \(0.9\))
    \State Compute linear transformation: \(L \leftarrow \mathrm{Linear}(T)\)
    \State Compute accelerated update: \(U \leftarrow L + \mu \cdot P\)
    \State \textbf{Output:} Accelerated token features \(U\)
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\subsection{Discussion}
The shift from fixed-resolution grids to flexible token-based representations marks a significant advance in diffusion-based generative modeling. Accelerated sampling techniques employing adaptive, high-order ODE solvers not only enhance convergence speed but also maintain high-resolution fidelity. The integration of these methods forms the basis of our proposed Accelerated Flexible Diffusion Transformer (AFiT), which unifies dynamic token acceleration, high-order numerical integration, and joint end-to-end training. Together, these developments indicate a strong trend toward architectures that are both resolution flexible and computationally efficient, paving the way for the next generation of diffusion models embodied by AFiT.

