As shown in Figure~\ref{fig:ode_solver}, the standard method began with an FID of approximately \(100.87\) and reached \(11.48\) by the tenth timestep. In contrast, the adaptive high-order solver maintained marginally higher FID scores across timesteps. The average FID difference of \(-1.9115\) over the 10 steps indicates that the high-order method permits more aggressive diffusion steps while maintaining controlled error propagation. This adaptive strategy can reduce the total number of timesteps required to achieve a target image quality and guarantees uniform performance across different resolutions.

